 1583:     (p,q,r) cell IDs that need to be searched.
 1584:     
 1585:     Through the course of running VoidFinder on an algorithm, searching adjacent
 1586:     grid cells at the various (p,q,r) locations will require unknown amounts of memory,
 1587:     so this class comes with a resize() method.  During a run, the memory held by this class
 1588:     will grow larger and larger, but ultimately there has to be 1 galaxy in the survey whose
 1589:     grid search for the next nearest neighbor is the farthest.  If this distance possible to 
 1590:     compute ahead of time, we would just pre-allocate that many rows, but that would be a 
 1591:     very expensive overhead so instead we provide the resize() method.  In practice the number
 1592:     of resizes is very small and quickly converges to a reasonable limit.
 1593:     
 1594:     For example, if the largest grid size that needs to be searched is 50 cells wide we need
 1595:     50^3 = 125,000 slots (times 3 for pqr and times sizeof(CELL_ID_t) total bytes, so 750kb for
 1596:     a 50x50x50 grid search)
 1597:     
 1598:     
 1599:     Parameters
 1600:     ==========
 1601:     
 1602:     level : int

 1604:         3D space, we use a cubic formula.  For level 0 we need 1 cell, for level
 1605:         2 we need the 3x3x3 = 27 cell IDs, for level 3 we need the 5x5x5 = 125 cell IDs, and
 1606:         in general for level n > 0 we need (2*n + 1)^3 rows of cell ID memory.
